This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a method to learn object representations that are invariant to affine transformations. It also uses convolutional neural networks (CNNs) which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper also involves training the CNNs, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The use of a regularizer to enforce circular patterns in the weights of the spatial filters suggests that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The paper's focus on improving data-efficiency and generalization suggests that it could belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's use of the Traffic Sign data set suggests that it could also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category, as this data set is commonly used in natural language processing tasks.
